Im feudal law. An estate in land held of a superior on condition of rendering him services. 2 Bl. Comm. 105. An inheritable right to the use and occupation of lands, held on condition of rendering services to the lord or proprietor, who himself retains the property in the lands. See Spel. Feuds, c. 1.:

In this sense the word is the same as "feod,'" "feodum," '"feudum," "fief," or "fee."

Im Saxon and old German law. An enmity, or species of private war, existing between the family of a murdered man and the family of his slayer; a combination ofthe former to take vengeance upon the latter. See DEADLY Freup;

The possession of the goods of fugitives. Fleta, lib. 1, c. 147.

FLET, home.

